#: ../../../reference/random/bit_generators/pcg64.rst:2
msgid "Permuted congruential generator (64-bit, PCG64)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._pcg64.PCG64:2
msgid "BitGenerator for the PCG-64 pseudo-random number generator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._pcg64.PCG64:0
msgid "Parameters"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._pcg64.PCG64:22
msgid "**seed**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._pcg64.PCG64:-1
msgid "{None, int, array_like[ints], SeedSequence}, optional"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._pcg64.PCG64:8
msgid ""
"A seed to initialize the `BitGenerator`. If None, then fresh, unpredictable "
"entropy will be pulled from the OS. If an ``int`` or ``array_like[ints]`` is "
"passed, then it will be passed to `SeedSequence` to derive the initial "
"`BitGenerator` state. One may also pass in a `SeedSequence` instance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._pcg64.PCG64:25
msgid "Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._pcg64.PCG64:26
msgid ""
"PCG-64 is a 128-bit implementation of O'Neill's permutation congruential "
"generator ([R4523891264fe-1]_, [R4523891264fe-2]_). PCG-64 has a period of :"
"math:`2^{128}` and supports advancing an arbitrary number of steps as well "
"as :math:`2^{127}` streams. The specific member of the PCG family that we "
"use is PCG XSL RR 128/64 as described in the paper ([R4523891264fe-2]_)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._pcg64.PCG64:32
msgid ""
"`PCG64` provides a capsule containing function pointers that produce "
"doubles, and unsigned 32 and 64- bit integers. These are not directly "
"consumable in Python and must be consumed by a `Generator` or similar object "
"that supports low-level access."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._pcg64.PCG64:37
msgid ""
"Supports the method :meth:`advance` to advance the RNG an arbitrary number "
"of steps. The state of the PCG-64 RNG is represented by 2 128-bit unsigned "
"integers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._pcg64.PCG64:41
msgid "**State and Seeding**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._pcg64.PCG64:43
msgid ""
"The `PCG64` state vector consists of 2 unsigned 128-bit values, which are "
"represented externally as Python ints. One is the state of the PRNG, which "
"is advanced by a linear congruential generator (LCG). The second is a fixed "
"odd increment used in the LCG."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._pcg64.PCG64:48
msgid ""
"The input seed is processed by `SeedSequence` to generate both values. The "
"increment is not independently settable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._pcg64.PCG64:51
msgid "**Parallel Features**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._pcg64.PCG64:53
msgid ""
"The preferred way to use a BitGenerator in parallel applications is to use "
"the `SeedSequence.spawn` method to obtain entropy values, and to use these "
"to generate new BitGenerators:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._pcg64.PCG64:61
msgid "**Compatibility Guarantee**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._pcg64.PCG64:63
msgid ""
"`PCG64` makes a guarantee that a fixed seed will always produce the same "
"random integer stream."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._pcg64.PCG64:67
msgid "References"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../docstring of numpy.random._pcg64.PCG64:68
msgid ""
